"short_id":"zt0n6v","short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/zt0n6v","created_at":"2024-01-15T09:51:28.000-06:00","title":"RSA is deceptively simple (and fun)","url":"https://ntietz.com/blog/rsa-deceptively-simple/","score":6,"flags":0,"comment_count":0,"description":"","description_plain":"","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/zt0n6v/rsa_is_deceptively_simple_fun","submitter_user":{"username":"kzisme","created_at":"2017-02-14T23:06:03.000-06:00","is_admin":false,"about":"","is_moderator":false,"karma":1402,"avatar_url":"/avatars/kzisme-100.png","invited_by_user":"awal"},"user_is_author":false,"tags":["cryptography"]},{"short_id":"exrbix","short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/exrbix","created_at":"2024-01-15T08:59:14.000-06:00","title":"The First DOS Machine (2007)","url":"http://dosmandrivel.blogspot.com/2007/11/first-dos-machine.html","score":5,"flags":0,"comment_count":1,"description":"","description_plain":"","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/exrbix/first_dos_machine_2007","submitter_user":{"username":"calvin","created_at":"2014-07-01T06:47:13.000-05:00","is_admin":false,"about":"Soon we will all have special names... names designed to make the cathode ray tube resonate.\r\n\r\nDavid Chisnall stan account.","is_moderator":false,"karma":101404,"avatar_url":"/avatars/calvin-100.png","invited_by_user":"nbyouri","github_username":"NattyNarwhal"},"user_is_author":false,"tags":["historical"]},{"short_id":"wztddn","short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/wztddn","created_at":"2024-01-15T08:56:35.000-06:00","title":"How to Fix Dependency Hell","url":"","score":1,"flags":0,"comment_count":0,"description":"\u003cp\u003eOK, let’s say your project depends on two big monolithic libraries that share dependencies in different, incompatible, versions.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIf you have the time, just fork, patch and move on.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIf you don’t, you’ll probably decide to rollback to earlier, compatible, versions. In the best case scenario you’ll miss features, in the worst, you’ll miss security updates.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eEventually though, some libraries (and its dependencies) will get so old, that you won’t even be able to rollback anymore. Just think of how many amazing, feature-complete, “public archives” are out there.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eOK, now, what if the interpreter knew \u003cem\u003eat runtime\u003c/em\u003e the specific versions of dependencies of each library. As long as the interpreter version is compatible (baby-steps), things should just work. Right?!\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eSo if you pip install X, which depends on Z==1.0, and pip install Y, which depends on Z==0.7, pip would install Z==1.0 \u003cem\u003eand\u003c/em\u003e Z==0.7. And, at runtime, the Python interpreter would know which version to use based on the current package specified dependencies – the dependencies would move from the project to the packages.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eBased on PEPs \u003ca href=\"https://peps.python.org/pep-0518/\" rel=\"ugc\"\u003e518\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"https://peps.python.org/pep-0665\" rel=\"ugc\"\u003e665\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"https://peps.python.org/pep-0723/\" rel=\"ugc\"\u003e723\u003c/a\u003e this could really be implemented.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eI don’t know, maybe I’m just being silly, what do you think?\u003c/p\u003e\n","description_plain":"OK, let's say your project depends on two big monolithic libraries that share dependencies in different, incompatible, versions.\r\n\r\nIf you have the time, just fork, patch and move on.\r\n\r\nIf you don't, you'll probably decide to rollback to earlier, compatible, versions. In the best case scenario you'll miss features, in the worst, you'll miss security updates.\r\n\r\nEventually though, some libraries (and its dependencies) will get so old, that you won't even be able to rollback anymore. Just think of how many amazing, feature-complete, \"public archives\" are out there.\r\n\r\nOK, now, what if the interpreter knew _at runtime_ the specific versions of dependencies of each library. As long as the interpreter version is compatible (baby-steps), things should just work. Right?!\r\n\r\nSo if you pip install X, which depends on Z==1.0, and pip install Y, which depends on Z==0.7, pip would install Z==1.0 _and_ Z==0.7. And, at runtime, the Python interpreter would know which version to use based on the current package specified dependencies -- the dependencies would move from the project to the packages.\r\n\r\nBased on PEPs [518](https://peps.python.org/pep-0518/), [665](https://peps.python.org/pep-0665), [723](https://peps.python.org/pep-0723/) this could really be implemented.\r\n\r\nI don't know, maybe I'm just being silly, what do you think?","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/wztddn/how_fix_dependency_hell","submitter_user":{"username":"0x67757300","created_at":"2023-12-08T10:04:30.000-06:00","is_admin":false,"about":"","is_moderator":false,"karma":48,"avatar_url":"/avatars/0x67757300-100.png","invited_by_user":"LenFalken"},"user_is_author":true,"tags":["python"]},{"short_id":"jfwwyi","short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/jfwwyi","created_at":"2024-01-15T08:18:19.000-06:00","title":"SQLite: Wal2 Mode Notes","url":"https://www.sqlite.org/cgi/src/doc/wal2/doc/wal2.md","score":16,"flags":0,"comment_count":2,"description":"","description_plain":"","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/jfwwyi/sqlite_wal2_mode_notes","submitter_user":{"username":"pondidum","created_at":"2021-01-05T10:19:41.000-06:00","is_admin":false,"about":"","is_moderator":false,"karma":799,"avatar_url":"/avatars/pondidum-100.png","invited_by_user":"jussi"},"user_is_author":false,"tags":["databases"]},{"short_id":"jsjdye","short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/jsjdye","created_at":"2024-01-15T07:41:31.000-06:00","title":"Ruffle: 2023 in review","url":"https://ruffle.rs/blog/2024/01/14/2023-in-review","score":19,"flags":0,"comment_count":1,"description":"","description_plain":"","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/jsj